<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-04-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-04-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="636" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d636">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/1093.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Mexican Chargé d’Affaires</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-04-07"><hi rend="italic">April 7,
                                1911</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 447.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                            receipt of the embassy’s note of the 26th ultimo, stating that the
                            governor of Sonora has reported that armed bands have invaded that State
                            from its northern boundary, and communicating to the Department a
                            request of your Government that steps be taken to prevent the movement
                            of such armed groups toward Mexican territory.</p>
                        <p>Copies of your note have been sent to the War Department and the
                            Department of Justice.</p>
                        <p>Accept [etc.],</p>
                        <closer>(For <signed>Mr. Knox</signed>.)<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson</hi>.</signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>